 malicious behaviors characteristic of sophisticated ransomware families. The malware employs significant obfuscation by dynamically resolving APIs at runtime (sub_401001) using XOR-based string decryption (key 0xF0) to hide its reliance on cryptographic and network libraries. Its primary functionality includes recursive directory traversal (sub_405698) and file encryption using the Windows Cryptographic Service Provider (RSA/AES via Advapi32.dll). Key behavioral indicators include a hardcoded exclusion list of system directories (e.g., Windows, Program Files, AppData) and extensions (.exe, .dll, .sys) to ensure system stability during encryption, the appending of the '.CONTI' extension to victim files, and the dropping of a ransom note named 'CONTI_README.txt'. Concrete IOCs include the XOR keys 0xF0 and 0x99 used for obfuscation and the specific ransom note filename.", "id": "0fd062f86151b9d49d65b8f12c52737600bff8bb3462aba7bf23d820bf4d5518-file-palm"}]}}}